Q) Develop a Dockerfile to build and deploy a simple web application (for example, a Python Flask or 
Node.js app). Explain the purpose of each Dockerfile instruction (FROM, RUN, COPY, EXPOSE, CMD) 
and verify the container creation using relevant Docker commands


CODE: 

Step 0: Prerequisites 
Make sure you have Docker installed. Check with: 
docker --version 

Step 1: Create a project folder 
mkdir flask_docker_lab 
cd flask_docker_lab 

Step 2: Create a simple Flask app 
 app.py: 
from flask import Flask 
app = Flask(__name__) 
@app.route("/") 
def home(): 
return "Hello from Docker!" 
if __name__ == "__main__": 
app.run(host="0.0.0.0", port=5000) 

Step 3: Create requirements file 
 requirements.txt: 
flask 

Step 4: Create Dockerfile 
FROM python:3.9-slim 
WORKDIR /app 
COPY . /app 
RUN pip install -r requirements.txt 
EXPOSE 5000 
CMD ["python", "app.py"] 

Step 6: Build Docker Image 
docker build -t flaskapp . 

Step 7: Run Docker Container 
docker run -d -p 5000:5000 flaskapp 

Step 8: Verify Container 
docker ps 
http://localhost:5000 





Q) Deploy a Dockerized application on a Kubernetes cluster using kubectl commands. Create and 
analyze the configuration files for Pods, Deployments, and Services, and explain how Kubernetes 
manages container orchestration and scaling

0) Quick checks :

minikube status 
docker images 
If docker images shows flaskapp:latest, continue. If not, build it: 
# from your project folder with Dockerfile and app.py 
docker build -t flaskapp:latest . 

1) Make the image available to Minikube  
minikube image load flaskapp:latest

2) Create Deployment YAML (deployment.yaml) 
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: flask-deployment
  labels:
    app: flaskapp
spec:
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: flaskapp
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: flaskapp
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: flask-container
        image: flaskapp:latest
        imagePullPolicy: IfNotPresent
        ports:
        - containerPort: 5000

3) Create Service YAML (service.yaml)

apiVersion: v1
kind: Service
metadata:
  name: flask-service
spec:
  type: NodePort
  selector:
    app: flaskapp
  ports:
  - port: 5000
    targetPort: 5000
    nodePort: 30007

4) Apply the manifests
kubectl apply -f deployment.yaml 
kubectl apply -f service.yaml

5) Verify resources & health 
kubectl get deployments 
kubectl get pods -w 

6) Access the app 
Get the Minikube IP and open in browser: 
minikube ip  
# e.g. 192.168.49.2 
# http://<minikube-ip>:30007  e.g. http://192.168.49.2:30007





Q) Set up a Puppet Master and Agent architecture in a Linux environment. Configure a pull-based setup 
where the Puppet Agent retrieves configurations from the Master. Demonstrate configuration 
updates and validate synchronization. 

STEP 1 — Install Puppet Server & Puppet Agent 

wget https://apt.puppet.com/puppet7-release-focal.deb 
sudo dpkg -i puppet7-release-focal.deb 
sudo apt update 
sudo apt install puppetserver puppet-agent -y 

STEP 2 — Start Puppet Server 

Start puppetserver 
sudo systemctl start puppetserver 
sudo systemctl enable puppetserver 

STEP 3 — Configure Puppet Agent to talk to Master 

sudo nano /etc/puppetlabs/puppet/puppet.conf 
Add this under [agent]: 
server = puppet-local 
certname = puppet-local 
environment = production 

STEP-4 Restart Puppet Agent service: 

sudo systemctl restart puppet 
sudo systemctl enable puppet 

STEP 5 — Create a Manifest to Test Synchronization 
Create the main manifest file: 
sudo nano /etc/puppetlabs/code/environments/production/manifests/site.pp 

Add: 

node default { 
file { '/tmp/myfile.txt': 
ensure  => present, 
content => "Hello from Puppet Master!", 
} 
} 


STEP 6 — Pull Configuration from Master 
Run agent: 
sudo /opt/puppetlabs/bin/puppet agent --test 

Check the file: 
cat /tmp/myfile.txt 
You should see: 
Hello from Puppet Master!
